english:
  title: Memorial in Gratitude for Appointment as Examiner of the Civil Service Examination
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The power to select talents through the examination—truly it requires the greatest skill. Yet the royal command has mistakenly fallen upon one so small and insignificant as I. Reflecting upon this grace and honor, I am seized by both joy and trepidation.

    Your servant humbly reflects: I am but a decaying scholar, born with a dull and feeble nature. In my youth I took the examination, yet shamefully failed to inscribe my name upon the golden register. Only in middle years did I gain office, fortunately soiling the seat of the Jade Hall. Though elevated above the common scholar's rank, I never rose to that of court attendant—my hair grew white as a crane's before my waist was girded with the ornamental belt. Only after Your Majesty's ascension did I at last tread the path of imperial favor. Long I served in the drafting office, yet I failed to embellish the sacred wisdom with proper refinement. Twice appointed as examiner, yet I could not gather all the talented and worthy. I dared hope only that Your Majesty's boundless magnanimity would overlook my former shortcomings.

    Now, as the appointment to the Prime Minister's office is bestowed, and the conduct of the examinations entrusted to my hands—positions which the world deems fit only for established masters of letters, and which few have ever held even once—how can I alone possess such extraordinary talent to be thrice appointed to such duties? This surely springs from...

    Governance first summons the truly gifted; virtue holds that cultivation of letters is paramount. Your Majesty, deeming this humble servant somewhat diligent in study, now entrusts me with the examination of candidates. I pledge to apply all my energy to assessing their abilities, to discover the rough jade concealing hidden talent, to polish it with care, and present it to court—thus contributing to the civilizing influence of benevolent rule.
  footnotes:
    - The 'golden register' (金榜) refers to the public posting of successful examination candidates.
    - The 'Jade Hall' (玉堂) was a prestigious office for talented scholars and officials.
    - '''Ornamental belt'' (犀帶) symbolizes an official''s rank and dignity.'
    - This is a formal memorial of gratitude written upon receiving appointment as chief examiner of the civil service examination, expressing both humility before the honor and commitment to fulfilling the duties faithfully.
